title: For Sale:  $$$$$  Browning 525 Citori 3Bbl Engraved, Boxed Set NICE $$##%%
postcontent: Manufacturer: BrowningModel: 525 Citori Engraved 3-Bbl Boxed Set!Barrel Length: 30 inchGauge: 20g, 28g, 410gCapacity: 2A gently used Browning 525 Citori 3 barreled over-under matching set, made with extreme care and precision by the finest artisans in Miroku, Japan. Comes in the Browning factory-fitted leather box, with leather reinforced corners, faux inside fur, flipup luggage locks, and brass feet for when it stands handle up. I was expecting a full complement of chokes for it and there is a big compartment in the box for them, but all you get here is what is sitting on the barrels: two long Browning goldtipped Skeet choke tubes for both 410 and 20g, and only one of the said Browning Sk choke tubes for the top barrel of the 28g set, although the bottom barrel is also threaded for chokes. Some of the choke tubes have tiny dings at their muzzles, but nothing serious. All three double barrels are perfectly matched and numbered to the receiver and the forearm, and fashioned to give similar sight picture and weight for near-identical swing feel, no matter which caliber is being fired. It features the single trigger that fires the top barrel first and readies the other firing pin, and if you don't fire the lower barrel the ejector only kicks out the upper empty. It was owned by an old skeet guy with too many guns, but he did shoot this one once in a while. It looks like his favorite caliber in this set was the 20g, as that barrel seems to be the one that's the farthest from looking unfired here. I didn't say it had the most wear because it barely shows any wear! Examining all 3 barrel sets, though, it is striking how little wear they have. You will find a tiny scratch or nick on a vent rib or the side of a barrel, but the only scratches worth mentioning here are the small ones right at the muzzle of the 20g set, about 1/16" long or less, on both sides of the top and bottom barrels, maybe from a brief rub on asphalt possibly, but hard to notice unless you look for them. The forearm looks wonderful too, from the same gorgeous chunk of walnut that the receiver is mounted in, and of course with the same soft satin finish as the stock. The only flaw to mention on it is that the front edge of the schnabel-style curve has some very minor little dings that pepper the edge line and blunt it a bit- very minor but if I fail to mention it somebody will bitch about it for sure. Lastly, the stock looks similarly wonderful, but is also not entirely flawless. The metal there looks wonderful, no flaws or nicks to report on it, but the beautiful wood does have a few minor scratches and rubs from light field use. The low-cut, hand-checkered diamonds all look mostly as they came from Miroku, but you'll see they have very minor point rounding in places, again from low to moderate field usage. Looking closely at that region, the only real wear showing is at the pointed forward edge of the pistol grip- very minor rounding of the edge there. Moving rearward, the left has a very shallow 2-inch long minor crease near the first cheek support , but little else to mention on that side. Moving to the right side, about the same length crease is there, but farther back, along with a few tiny marks scattered around, but again nothing to arouse any alarm or ire, just minimal, honest wear that can easily be corrected if necessary. The cheek rest looks to be adjustable up and down, and the recoil pad is hard rubber mounted on an ingenious internal recoil-reducing part that slides into the stock and compresses against a strong spring to blunt and prolong the sensation, for a big reduction to the shoulder. In addition, the 20g barrels are both ported, for a further reduction in muzzle rise. An extremely beautiful and functional piece of shootable art, no less, so belly up and bid! The distance from the front of the trigger to the extended butt plate is almost 15 inches. The owner had a piece of what looks like black naugahide stuck to the entire cheekpiece upper surface, and a bit of that is starting to curl up on the left side bottom edge.
